<subSubSection id="B6A6AFB4AE48CF2BFF79FF6FFBC0FE31" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="description">
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF79FF6FFE80FF6D" blockId="23.[151,1014,151,214]" box="[151,311,187,214]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<figureCitation id="6687E0BAAE48CF2BFF79FF6FFE80FF6D" box="[151,311,187,214]" captionStart="FIGURES 228–247" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[157,1425,191,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-16@22.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 228–247. Male genitalia. 228–233―Anaceratagallia (Anaceratagallia) aciculata, 234–236―A. (A.) kungradica, 237–238―A. (A.) aciculata sensu Khatri et al., 2010, 239–240―A. (A.) seriphidii, holotype, 241–245―A. (A.) acuteangulata, 246–247―A. (Oedicora) kerzhneri. 228, 230, 232, 234, 237, 239, 241–242, 246―penis, lateral view, 229, 231, 233, 235–236, 240, 243–245―male anal collar appendage, 238―end of pygofer lobe and male anal collar appendage, 247―end of pygofer lobe. 234–236―after Dubovsky (1967), 237–238―after Khatri et al. (2010)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4398510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4398510/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Figs. 241–245</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF79FED7FBC0FE31" blockId="23.[151,1437,259,717]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF79FED7FE9EFEA6" bold="true" box="[151,297,259,285]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Description.</emphasis>
Only one series of specimens from Northern Caucasus (
<collectingRegion id="3C7832DDAE48CF2BFC72FED7FB8CFEA6" box="[924,1083,259,285]" country="Russia" name="North Ossetia" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">North Ossetia</collectingRegion>
, the Ardon River Basin, SadonUnal Depression) was investigated. Penis in side view with straight or slightly convex serrated ventral crest in basal two-thirds and with dorsal margin strongly expanded in basal half (
<figureCitation id="6687E0BAAE48CF2BFC4CFE9FFBFCFEDE" box="[930,1099,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 228–247" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[157,1425,191,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-16@22.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 228–247. Male genitalia. 228–233―Anaceratagallia (Anaceratagallia) aciculata, 234–236―A. (A.) kungradica, 237–238―A. (A.) aciculata sensu Khatri et al., 2010, 239–240―A. (A.) seriphidii, holotype, 241–245―A. (A.) acuteangulata, 246–247―A. (Oedicora) kerzhneri. 228, 230, 232, 234, 237, 239, 241–242, 246―penis, lateral view, 229, 231, 233, 235–236, 240, 243–245―male anal collar appendage, 238―end of pygofer lobe and male anal collar appendage, 247―end of pygofer lobe. 234–236―after Dubovsky (1967), 237–238―after Khatri et al. (2010)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4398510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4398510/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Figs. 241–242</figureCitation>
). Male anal collar appendage bifurcate, with dorsal angle pointing up and ventral angle directed back (
<figureCitation id="6687E0BAAE48CF2BFC2BFEBBFBDBFE31" box="[965,1132,367,394]" captionStart="FIGURES 228–247" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[157,1425,191,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-16@22.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 228–247. Male genitalia. 228–233―Anaceratagallia (Anaceratagallia) aciculata, 234–236―A. (A.) kungradica, 237–238―A. (A.) aciculata sensu Khatri et al., 2010, 239–240―A. (A.) seriphidii, holotype, 241–245―A. (A.) acuteangulata, 246–247―A. (Oedicora) kerzhneri. 228, 230, 232, 234, 237, 239, 241–242, 246―penis, lateral view, 229, 231, 233, 235–236, 240, 243–245―male anal collar appendage, 238―end of pygofer lobe and male anal collar appendage, 247―end of pygofer lobe. 234–236―after Dubovsky (1967), 237–238―after Khatri et al. (2010)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4398510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4398510/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Figs. 243–245</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B6A6AFB4AE48CF2BFF29FE47FE58FE4E" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF29FE47FEEDFE69" blockId="23.[151,1437,259,717]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF29FE47FE90FE16" bold="true" box="[199,295,403,429]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Biology.</emphasis>
Collected in mountainous-xerophyte plant community in arid depression on southern slopes of Skalisty Mtn. Range.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF29FE0FFE58FE4E" blockId="23.[151,1437,259,717]" box="[199,495,475,501]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF29FE0FFEC5FE4E" bold="true" box="[199,370,475,501]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Calling signal.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B6A6AFB4AE48CF2BFF29FE2BFE31FDD9" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF29FE2BFE31FDD9" blockId="23.[151,1437,259,717]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF29FE2BFED6FDA2" bold="true" box="[199,353,511,537]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="86ABBCAFAE48CF2BFE86FE2BFE2BFDA2" box="[360,412,511,537]" name="Italy" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Italy</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="86ABBCAFAE48CF2BFE49FE2BFE4EFDA2" box="[423,505,511,537]" name="Greece" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Greece</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="86ABBCAFAE48CF2BFDEAFE2BFDE3FDA2" box="[516,596,511,537]" name="Turkey" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Turkey</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="9A2D81CEAE48CF2BFD8DFE2BFC99FDA1" author="Zakhvatkin, A. A." box="[611,814,511,538]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" pagination="149 - 176" refId="ref14510" refString="Zakhvatkin, A. A. (1946) Studies on the Homoptera of Turkey. I-VII. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 97 (6), 149 - 176. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1946. tb 00278. x" type="journal article" year="1946">Zakhvatkin, 1946</bibRefCitation>
), Northern Caucasus (North Ossetia). The records from 
<collectingCountry id="86ABBCAFAE48CF2BFF79FDF7FF43FD86" box="[151,244,547,573]" name="Ukraine" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="86ABBCAFAE48CF2BFEEEFDF7FE31FD86" box="[256,390,547,573]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, and Central Asia by 
<bibRefCitation id="9A2D81CEAE48CF2BFD95FDF7FCE0FD86" author="Logvinenko, V. N." box="[635,855,547,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" pagination="19 - 27" refId="ref13586" refString="Logvinenko, V. N. (1984) New data on the fauna of Auchenorrhyncha (Homoptera) of Ukraine. In: Taxonomiya i zoogeografiya nasekomyh. Sbornik nauchnyh trudov. &quot; Naukova Dumka &quot;, Kiev, pp. 19 - 27. [in Russian]" type="book chapter" year="1984">Logvinenko (1984)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="9A2D81CEAE48CF2BFC8AFDF7FBA1FD86" author="Mityaev, I. D." box="[868,1046,547,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" refId="ref13797" refString="Mityaev, I. D. (1971) Cicadinea of Kazakhstan. Keys for identification of species. &quot; Nauka &quot; Publ., Alma-Ata, 211 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1971">Mityaev (1971)</bibRefCitation>
, and Dubovskiy (1966) in fact belong to 
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF03FD93FEB2FDDA" box="[237,261,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">A.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="39BC87BCAE48CF2BFEE2FD93FEC8FDDA" authorityName=": Dubovsky" authorityYear="1966" box="[268,383,583,610]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Anaceratagallia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevis" subGenus="Anaceratagallia">
(
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFEFBFD93FE91FDDA" box="[277,294,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">A</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFED0FD93FEC8FDDA" box="[318,383,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">laevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B6A6AFB4AE48CF2BFF29FDBFFF5AFD76" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF29FDBFFF5AFD76" blockId="23.[151,1437,259,717]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF29FDBFFE8CFD3E" bold="true" box="[199,315,619,645]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Remarks.</emphasis>
Mountainous-xerophyte plant communities are typical of arid regions of Transcaucasia and the Mediterranean. Thus, the occurence of this species in similar biotopes North of the Great Caucasus Mtn. Range is quite natural.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
